anagement and assurance of security risks and resilience. Shifts in published and emerging guidance will illustrate developments and expectations with nuclear specific and generic guidance including: • CPNI Securing Industrial Control Systems • NIST SP 800-82 Guide to Industrial Control Systems (ICS) Security R2 • NIST Cyber Security Framework (CSF) • IAEA Nuclear Security Series Computer security of instrumentation and control systems at nuclear facilities • IAEA NST022 and NST036 • IEC 62859 Ed. 1.0 • IEC 62645 Ed. 2.0 The authors offer some guiding key principles - relevant good practice - that should form the basis of implementing effective cyber security by nuclear licensees. These principles, which reflect international standards development, will be explored in more detail in a follow-on paper by the same authors. Nuclear Industries Security Regulations (NISR) 2003 [3] create obligations on duty holders that are additional to nuclear and conventional safety obligations that are contained within the Nuclear Installations Act 1965 [4], the Health & Safety at Work Act 1974 [5], associated regulations, and nuclear Licence Conditions. Other industry sectors have similar challenges and developments to address similar issues will illustrate the necessity and applicable good practice. It is an expectation that, in due course, there will be a move to one overall set of objectives for both nuclear safety and nuclear security. This reflects the convergence and balance required. {\textcopyright} 2016, Institution of Engineering and Technology. All rights reserved.},
