@inproceedings{,
abstract = {Risk acceptance decisions are essential in any risk management system. However, in occupational environments, this is a problematic and challenging issue, since there are several factors that can influence the decision-making process regarding risk acceptance. This theoretical work aims to analyze the main factors that play an important role in the risk acceptance in occupational environments, through a literature review. This study showed that risk acceptance seems to be affected by several factors: risk and benefits, organizational and personal factors. Regarding the organizational factors, dimensions such as safety climate, safety culture and work flexibility can be considered. Moreover, some important personal factors can also be considered. Thus, risk acceptance decisions can contain moral judgments, values, ethical concerns and emotions. It also can be influenced by trust and perception of risks and benefits. This study shows that the influence of these factors can lead to several discrepancies in the risk acceptance decisions among the different countries, organizations, managers and employees. Therefore, risks are accepted based on its acceptance conditions. This study also shows the need of involving all stakeholders in order to eliminate the limitations of individual decisions, and to make the risk acceptance process more effective and, consequently, improve the performance of the safety management system. More studies regarding the implications the factors analyzed in the risk acceptance decisions for in occupational environments are needed. Copyright {\textcopyright} (2012) by IAPSAM & ESRA.},
